**[src/pick/index.ts:68–75]** — Good pattern, but sequential confirmation
```
// Current (lines 69–75):
const listProc = Bun.spawn(listArgs, { stdout: 'pipe' });
const listOutput = await new Response(listProc.stdout).text();
await listProc.exited;  // ❌ Wait for process + read output is inherently sequential
```
**Issue:** You're already avoiding the TTY race (good!), but `Response.body` drain + `exited` is sequential. Minimal real-world cost (small list), but mentioned as a pattern to note.

**[src/utils/session-time.ts:18–54]** — Early chunk sizes too conservative
```
// Current:
const CHUNK_SIZES = [16384, 65536, 262144]; // 16KB, 64KB, 256KB
// But line 29: if (chunkSize > size * 2 && chunkSize !== CHUNK_SIZES[0]) break;
```
**Issue:** Break condition is buggy—allows CHUNK_SIZES[0] (16KB) even when file is tiny. Also, comment says "30+ file-history-snapshot lines (60KB+)", but largest chunk tried is 256KB. For real 60KB+ sessions, only 3 reads max, but many sessions may need all 3 attempts.

**Suggestion:** Either cap at observed max (~256KB is reasonable) or skip break logic if size is truly tiny. The early-exit on line 29 saves 1-2 reads for very small files.

**[src/list/summary.ts:101–111]** — Triple read on small files
```
// Current:
const headText = await file.slice(0, CHUNK_SIZE).text();  // Read 1
const tailText = await file.slice(start, size).text();    // Read 2
if (size <= CHUNK_SIZE * 2) {
  const fullText = await file.text();                    // Read 3 ❌
```
**Issue:** For files ≤32KB, you read head+tail (2×), then read entire file (3×). Wastes 3 I/O ops when you only need 1.

**Suggestion:** 
```typescript
if (size <= CHUNK_SIZE * 2) {
  const fullText = headText.includes('\n' + tailText.split('\n')[0]!) 
    ? headText + tailText.slice(tailText.indexOf('\n')) 
    : await file.text();
  // or simpler: early-exit before reading head+tail
}
```
Or restructure: check size *before* reading chunks, then either read full or head+tail.

